nocence offers a fresh perspective on Blanchot's writings in general and on his dialogue with Hegel in particular. While staging innocence in its philosophical and literary dimensions, The Writing of Innocence provides singular readings of works by Kierkegaard, Agamben, Derrida, Nancy, Camus, Hugo, and Kafka.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInnocence (Psychology) 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Christianity. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848901840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438489018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438489018/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles